    "id": 573,
    "text": "the potentially harmful consequences of one's behaviour, where the risk of harm to persons, property, or normal University operations exists or can be reasonably foreseen. f. 'University Official' is a person employed by the University on an administrative, supervisory, academic, research, or support staff position. 5. Academic Dishonesty. Academic dishonesty is an act of fraud, which may include misrepresentation, deceit, falsification, or trickery of any kind committed by the student with the purpose, intent, or expectation of influencing a grade or other academic evaluation. Academic dishonesty also includes forgery and falsification of University academic documents, intentionally impeding or damaging the academic work of others, or assisting other students in acts of dishonesty. Common examples of academically dishonest behaviour include, but are not limited, to the following: NUST Postgraduate Student Handbook 63",
